<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_rings" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rings</title>
<introduction><p>
    In a sense the motivation for the mathematical definition of a ring in mathematics is more immediate than that for a group. From very early on in our mathematical training we are introduced to quite a rich variety of different <em>number systems</em> including the integers <m>\Z</m>, the rational numbers <m>\Q</m>, the real numbers <m>\R</m>, and the complex numbers <m>\C</m>. Roughly understood, a number system is a set together with two distinct operations, addition and multiplication, which are each reasonably well-behaved and moreover play nicely together. <xref ref="d_ring"/> makes precise exactly what me mean by this. 
</p></introduction>
<subsection xml:id="ss_ring_def_egs">
<title>Definition and examples</title>


<definition xml:id="d_ring">
<title>Ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
A <term>ring</term> is a triple <m>(R,+,\cdot)</m>, where <m>R</m> is a nonempty set, and <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> are binary operations 
<md>
    <mrow>R\times R \amp \xrightarrow{\phantom{XX}+\phantom{XX}} R \amp R\times R\amp \xrightarrow{\phantom{XX}\bullet\phantom{XX}} R</mrow>
</md>,
called <term>ring addition</term> and <term>ring multiplication</term>, respectively, that satisfy the following axioms. 
<ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>(R,+)</m> is an abelian group. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
          Ring multiplication is associative: <ie/>, <m>a\cdot(b\cdot c)=(a\cdot b)\cdot c</m> for all <m>a,b,c\in R</m>.   
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Ring multiplication distributes over ring addition: <ie/>, we have 
            <mdn>
                <mrow>a\cdot (b+c) \amp =a\cdot b+a\cdot c</mrow>
                <mrow>(b+c)\cdot d \amp =b\cdot d+c\cdot d</mrow>
            </mdn>
            for all <m>a,b,c,d\in R</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            There is a <term>multiplicative identity</term> element <m>1\in R</m> satisfying 
            <md number="yes" xml:id="eq_mult_id">1\cdot a=a\cdot 1=a</md> for all <m>a\in R</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
A ring <m>R</m> is <term>commutative</term> if its ring multiplication is commutative and <term>noncommutative</term> otherwise. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<warning>
    <p>
        The Dummit and Foote text does not include (iv) as one of the axioms a ring needs to satisfy.
Instead it distinguishes between rings <em>with</em> and <em>without identity</em>. We will not follow suit and will
conscientiously point out resulting discrepancies between our exposition and the bookâ€™s.
    </p>
</warning>
<convention>
    <p>
        Addition in a ring will always be denoted by <m>+</m>, and this notation will never be suppressed. In contrast, we are free to denote the ring multiplication operation in any manner we please, but will more often than not omit the notation in ring expressions. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Additionally we will use the following <em>integer multiple</em> notation: 
        <md>
            <mrow>n a \amp = \underset{n \text{ times}}{\underbrace{a+a+\cdots +a}} \amp a\in R, n\in \Z_{\geq 1}</mrow>
            <mrow>(-n)a \amp = n(-a) \amp a\in R, n\in \Z_{\geq 1}</mrow>
        </md>.
    </p>
</convention>
<p>
    As mentioned at the top, our definition of a ring is chosen to generalize the familiar number systems (<m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, <m>\C</m>) of our mathematical youth. That these sets are rings (indeed, commutative rings) with respect to their usual arithmetic operations is a result of arithmetic properties you learned long ago. We add to this collection the slightly more exotic modular rings <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for <m>n</m> a positive integer; the ring axiom identities for modular addition and multiplication follow directly from the corresponding identities for the integer operations.
</p>
<activity xml:id="spec_elem_comm_rings">
<title>Elementary commutative rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
The sets <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, and <m>\C</m> are all commutative rings with respect to their usual addition and multiplication operations. Additionally, for any positive integer <m>n</m>, the set <m>\Z/n\Z</m> is a commutative ring with respect to its modular addition and multiplication operations. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<example xml:id="eg_trivial_ring">
<title>Trivial ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
Show that a singleton <m>\{a\}</m> can be given a unique ring structure. We call such rings <term>trivial</term>. 
</p>
<p>
    Show that a ring <m>R</m> is trivial if and only if the equality <m>0=1</m> holds in <m>R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Left to the reader. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<p>
    We need not travel too far to find an examples of noncommutative rings. Matrix arithmetic furnishes us with a familiar enough example. 
</p>
<activity xml:id="spec_matrix_rings">
<title>Matrix rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring. Given a positive integer <m>n</m>, we define <m>\ML_n(R)</m> to be the set of all <m>n\times n</m> matrices with coefficients in <m>R</m>.  
</p>
<p>
    Given matrices <m>A=[a_{ij}],B=[b_{ij}]\in \ML_n(R)</m>, we define their sum <m>A+B</m> and product <m>AB</m> as follows: 
    <md>
        <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq_matrix_add">A+B \amp =[a_{ij}+b_{ij}]</mrow>
        <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq_matrix_prod">AB \amp = [c_{ij}] \amp c_{ij}=\sum_{k=1}^na_{ik}b_{kj}</mrow>
    </md>.
    The triple <m>(\ML_n(R), +,\cdot)</m>, where <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> are the matrix addition and multiplication operations defined above, is a ring called the <term>ring of <m>n\times n</m> matrices over <m>R</m></term> (or <term>with coefficients in <m>R</m></term>).
</p>
<p>
    If <m>n\geq 2</m>, then <m>\ML_n(R)</m> is a noncommutative ring, as an argument very similar to the one in <xref ref="eg_nonabelian_gln"/> shows. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<remark>
<title>Matrix rings</title>
<p>
We can remove the restriction that <m>R</m> be commutative in <xref ref="spec_matrix_rings"/>. In other words, the matrix operations <xref ref="eq_matrix_add"/> satisfy the ring axioms whether or not <m>R</m> is commutative. We will restrict our attention to the case where <m>R</m> is commutative, however, as here the algebraic properties of <m>\ML_n(R)</m> are somewhat simpler. In particular, when <m>R</m> is commutative, we can define a determinant function <m>\det\colon \ML_n(R)\rightarrow R</m> in the usual fashion, and <m>\det</m> enjoys essentially all of the properties you are familiar with in the case where <m>R=\R</m>. See <xref ref="th_matrix_rings"/> below.
</p>
</remark>



<p>
    We now dispense with the usual <q>general properties</q> result for our newly defined mathematical friends. 
</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop_ring_props">
    <title>Ring properties</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a ring. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The multiplicative identity element of <m>R</m> is unique: <ie/>, there is exactly one element of <m>R</m> satisfying the identity <xref ref="eq_mult_id"/>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>0a=a0=0</m> for all <m>a\in R</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>-a=(-1)a=a(-1)</m> for all <m>a\in R</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(-a)b=a(-b)=-ab</m> for all <m>a,b\in R</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We prove (1) and (2), leaving (3) and (4) to the reader.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If an element <m>b\in R</m> satisfies <m>ba=ab=a</m> for all <m>a\in R</m>, then in particular, it satisfies <m>b1=1</m>. But by definition of the the multiplicative identity, we have <m>b1=b</m>. Thus <m>b=1</m>, as desired. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We have 
                        <md>
                            <mrow>0a \amp =(0+0)a</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 0a+0a</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        Using the additive inverse <m>-0a</m>, we see that
                        <md>
                            <mrow>0a=0a+0a \amp \implies -0a+0a=-0a+0a+0a</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \implies 0=0+0a</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \implies 0=0a</mrow>
                        </md>,
                        as desired. A similar argument shows $a0=0$. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>


<p>
    Our matrix ring example is in fact an example of a <em>ring construction</em>: a method of building new rings from existing ones. The <em>product ring</em> construction is another such example. 
</p>
<activity xml:id="spec_ring_product">
<title>Product rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>I</m> be a nonempty set, and let <m>(R_i)_{i\in I}</m> be a family of rings indexed by <m>I</m>. We define an addition and multiplication operation on <m>R=\prod_{i\in I}R_i</m> as follows:
<md>
    <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq_product_ring_ops">R\times R \amp \xrightarrow{\phantom{XX}+\phantom{XX}} R 
        \amp R\times R\amp \xrightarrow{\phantom{XX}\bullet\phantom{XX}} R 
    </mrow>
    <mrow>(a_i)_{i\in I}, (b_i)_{i\in I} \amp \mapsto (a_i+b_i)_{i\in I}
        \amp (a_i)_{i\in I},(b_i)_{i\in I}\amp\mapsto (a_ib_i)_{i\in I}
    </mrow>
</md>.
In other words, addition and multiplication of tuples is defined component-wise. 
</p>
<p>
The triple <m>(R,+,\cdot)</m> is ring called the <term>product</term> of the rings <m>R_i</m>. Note that we have already seen that <m>(R,+)</m> is a group. (See <xref ref="prop_product_group"/>.) The identity element of <m>R</m> is the tuple <m>1=(1_{R_i})_{i\in I}</m>, where for all <m>i\in I</m>, <m>1_{R_i}</m> is the identity element of <m>R_i</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<p>
    Technically speaking, the <em>ring of functions</em> construction introduced next is just a special case of the product ring construction: that is, by <em>definition</em> we have 
    <me>
        \mathcal{F}(X,R)=R^X=\prod_{x\in X}R
    </me>.
    We include it nonetheless, as this construction (in this particular guise) is particular important in analysis contexts. 
</p>
<activity xml:id="spec_ring_of_functions">
<title>Ring of functions</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a ring, let <m>X</m> be a nonempty set, and let <m>\mathcal{F}(X,R)</m> be the set of all functions from <m>X</m> to <m>R</m>. Given functions <m>f,g\in F(X,R)</m> we define their sum <m>f+g</m> and product <m>fg</m> as follows: 
<md>
    <mrow>(f+g)(x) \amp = f(x)+g(x) \text{ for all } x\in X</mrow>
    <mrow>(fg)(x) \amp =f(x)g(x) \text{ for all } x\in X</mrow>
</md>. 
The triple <m>(\mathcal{F}(X,R),+,\cdot)</m>, where <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> are the function addition and multiplication operations defined above, is a ring called the <term>ring of functions</term> from <m>X</m> to <m>R</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    The additive identity of <m>\mathcal{F}(X,R)</m> is the zero function <m>0_X\colon X\rightarrow R</m> defined as <m>0_X(x)=0</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>; the multiplicative identity of <m>\mathcal{F}(X,R)</m> is the constant function <m>1_X\colon X\rightarrow R</m> defined as <m>1_X(x)=1</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<p>
    Another method of building a new ring from an existing one is to identify a <em>subring</em>. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_subring">
<title>Subring</title>
<statement>
<p>
A subset <m>S</m> of the ring <m>R</m> is a <term>subring</term> if it satisfies the following conditions. 
<ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>S</m> is a subgroup of <m>(R,+)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>1\in S</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>S</m> is closed under multiplication: <ie/>, for all <m>a,b\in S</m>, we have <m>ab\in S</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
It follows from the ring axioms that a subring <m>S</m> of <m>R</m> is itself a ring with respect to ring operations of <m>R</m>, restricted to <m>S</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<activity xml:id="spec_quadratic_fields">
<title>Quadratic extensions of <m>\Q</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>q\in \Q</m> be a rational number that does not have a rational square root, and let <m>\sqrt{q}</m> denote one of the two square roots of <m>q</m> lying in <m>\C</m>. We denote by <m>\Q[\sqrt{q}]</m> the subset of <m>\C</m> consisting of all rational linear combinations of <m>1</m> and <m>\sqrt{q}</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md number="yes">
        \Q[\sqrt{q}]=\{z\in \C\mid z=a+b\sqrt{q} \text{ for some } a,b\in \Q\}
    </md>.
The set <m>\Q[\sqrt{q}]</m> is a subring of <m>\C</m>, and hence a ring in its own right. 
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<definition xml:id="d_ring_center">
<title>Center of ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
The <term>center</term> of a ring <m>R</m>, denoted <m>Z(R)</m>, is the set of elements of <m>R</m> that commute with all elements of <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md number="yes">
        Z(R)=\{a\in R\mid ab=ba \text{ for all } b\in R\}
    </md>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_center">
<title>Center of a ring</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a ring. Show that <m>Z(R)</m> is a subring of <m>R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
First we show that <m>Z(R)</m> is a subring of <m>(R,+)</m>. From <xref ref="prop_ring_props"/> we know that <m>0\in Z(R)</m>. Next, assume <m>a,b\in Z(R)</m>. Given any <m>c\in R</m>, we have 
<md>
    <mrow>(a+b)c \amp =ac+bc=ca+cb</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp =ca+cb</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp = c(a+b)</mrow>
    <mrow>(-a)c \amp =a(-c)</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp =(-c)a</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp =c(-a)</mrow>
</md>,
and thus <m>a+b, -a\in Z(R)</m>.
</p>
<p>
    Next, we have <m>1\in Z(R)</m> by <xref ref="prop_ring_props"/>. Finally, we show that <m>Z(R)</m> is closed under multiplication. Assume <m>a,b\in Z(R)</m>. Given <m>c\in R</m>, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>(ab)c \amp = a(bc) </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =a(cb)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =(ac)b</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =(ca)b</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =c(ab)</mrow>
    </md>,
    showing <m>ab\in Z(R)</m>, as desired. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>

</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_rings_units_nilpotents">
<title>Units, zero divisors,nilpotents, idempotents</title>
<p>
    We will now discuss various types of special ring elements, starting with units. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_units">
<title>Units and multiplicative inverses</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>a</m> be an element of the nontrivial ring <m>R</m>. A <term>multiplicative inverse</term> of <m>a</m> is an element <m>b\in R</m> satisfying <m>ab=ba=1</m>. We denote <m>b=a^{-1}</m> in this case. The element <m>a</m> is a <term>unit</term> (or is <term>invertible</term>) if it has a multiplicative inverse. We denote by <m>R^*</m> the set of all units of <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow> R^* \amp =\{a\in R\mid a \text{ is invertible}\}</mrow>
    </md>.
It follows directly from the ring axioms that <m>R^*</m> is a group with respect to the ring multiplication operation. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
    As we have intimated on multiple occasions, the ring <m>M_n(R)</m>, for <m>R</m> an arbitrary commutative ring, behaves very much like the ring <m>M_n(\R)</m>. Let's make official some of these similarities, postponing a proof until later in the course. At some point we will be able to use our ring theory to prove a <em>universal identity</em> result allowing us to transfer certain familiar properties of familiar rings <q>defined over <m>\R</m> or <m>\C</m></q> (meaning to be revealed later) and import these to analogous rings defined over an arbitrary commutative ring <m>\R</m>.
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_matrix_rings">
<title>Matrix ring goodies</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            We can define a determinant function <m>\det \colon M_n(R)\rightarrow R</m> that can be computed by the usual expansion formula along any row or column of a matrix. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\det AB=\det A\det B</m> for all <m>A,B\in M_n(R)</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            For all <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> there is a matrix <m>A^\dagger</m>, called the <term>adjoint matrix</term> of <m>A</m>, satisfying 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>A\, A^\dagger=A^\dagger A= (\det A) I</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            For all <m>A\in M_n(R)</m>, <m>A</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\det A\in R^*</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    Postponed.
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<activity xml:id="spec_gen_lin_group_general">
<title>General linear group</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring, and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. We denote by <m>\GL_n(R)</m> the group of units of <m>\ML_n(R)</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md>
        <mrow>\GL_n(R) \amp =\{A\in \ML_n(R)\mid A \text{ is invertible}\}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \{A\in \ML_n(R)\mid \det A\in R^*\}</mrow>
    </md>.
</p>
</statement>
</activity>
<example xml:id="eg_units_product">
<title>Units in product rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
               Let <m>R</m> be a product ring <m>R=\prod_{i\in I}R_i</m>. Prove: <m>R^*=\prod_{i\in I}R_i^*</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>S=\mathcal{F}(X,R)</m> for some nonempty set <m>X</m>. Prove: 
                <md>
                    <mrow> S^*  \amp = \{f\in \mathcal{F}(X,R)\mid f(x)\in R^* \text{ for all } x\in X\} </mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Left to the reader.
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<definition xml:id="d_division_rings_fields">
<title>Division rings and fields</title>
<statement>
<p>
A nontrivial ring <m>R</m> is a <term>division ring</term> if every nonzero element of <m>R</m> is a unit: <ie/>, <m>R^*=R- \{0\}</m>. A <term>field</term> is a commutative division ring.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_division_rings">
<title>Division rings</title>
<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the given ring is a division ring, and whether it is a field. 
<ol cols="2">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\Z</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\Q</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\R</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\C</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for <m>n\geq 2</m> a positive integer. The answer depends on <m>n</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\Q[\sqrt{d}]</m>, where <m>d\in \Q</m> does not have a square root in <m>\Q</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\ML_n(R)</m>, for <m>R</m> a commutative ring and <m>n\geq 2</m>. 
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
We mainly leave this to the reader, restricting our comments to the rings <m>\Z/n\Z</m>, <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>, and <m>\ML_n(R)</m> .
</p>
<p>
We showed previously that
<md number="yes">
    <mrow>(\Z/n\Z)^* \amp =\{[a]_n\in \Z/n/Z\mid \gcd(a,n)=1\}</mrow>
</md>,
from whence it easily follows that <m>\Z/n\Z</m> is a field if and only if <m>n=p</m> is a prime integer. 
</p>
<p>
We claim <m>\Q[\sqrt[d]]</m> is a field. Assume <m>\alpha=a+b\sqrt{q}</m> is a nonzero element of <m>\Q[\sqrt{d}]</m>. This is true if and only if <m>a\ne 0</m> or <m>b\ne 0</m>. (If <m>\alpha=0</m> and <m>a</m> or <m>b</m> is nonzero, then we could write <m>\sqrt{q}=-a/b\in \Q</m> or <m>\sqrt{q}=-a/b\in \Q</m>). Contradiction.) Let <m>\beta=a-b\sqrt{q}</m>. We have 
<md number="yes">
    <mrow>\alpha\beta=a^2-b^2q \amp </mrow>
</md>,
and this is nonzero, since otherwise we would have <m>q=a^2/b^2</m>, contradicting the fact that <m>q</m> is not a square in <m>\Q</m>. Thus <m>\alpha</m> has inverse 
<md>
    \alpha^{-1}=\frac{1}{a^2-b^2q}(a-b\sqrt{q})\in \Q[\sqrt{d}]
</md>.
</p>
<p>
    Lastly, from <xref ref="th_matrix_rings"/>, we know that <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\det A\in R^*</m>. Assuming <m>n\geq 2</m>, it is easy to construct a nonzero matrix <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> with <m>\det A=0</m>. Thus <m>M_n(R)</m> is not a division ring. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<convention>
    <p>
        Having shown that <m>\Z/p\Z</m> is a field for <m>p</m> a prime integer, we will write <m>\F_p=\Z/p\Z</m> from now on. 
    </p>
</convention>
<definition xml:id="d_zero_divisors">
<title>Zero divisors and integral domains</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a ring. A nonzero element <m>a\in R</m> is a <term>zero divisor</term> if there exists a nonzero element <m>b\in R</m> satisfying <m>ab=0</m> or <m>ba=0</m>.
</p>
<p>
    A ring <m>R</m> is an <term>integral domain</term> if it is (i) commutative, and (ii) contains no zero divisors. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_zero_divisors">
<title>Zero divisors</title>
<statement>
<p>
For each of the rings in <xref ref="eg_division_rings"/>, determine all zero divisors and determine whether the ring is an integral domain. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
We leave most of this to the reader.
</p>
<p>
    One interesting observation is that <m>\Z/n\Z</m> has zero divisors if and only if <m>n</m> is not prime. It follows that <m>\Z/n\Z</m> is a field if and only if <m>\Z/n\Z</m>  is an integral domain! This interesting fact is generalized in <xref ref="th_finite_rings_fields"/> below.
</p>
<p>
    We are tempted to say that <m>A\in M_n(R)</m> is a zero divisor if and only if <m>\det A</m> is either zero or a zero divisor of <m>R</m>. Indeed, this is the case! However, even with <xref ref="th_matrix_rings"/> at our disposal, one of the implications involved is somewhat involved. The easy direction is the forward one: if <m>A</m> is a a zero divisor, then there is a nonzero matrix <m>B</m> such that <m>AB=0</m>; multiplying on the left by the adjoint matrix <m>A^\dagger</m>, we see that <m>(\det A)IB=(\det A)B=0</m>. Since <m>B\ne 0</m>, it follows that <m>\det A</m> is either zero or a zero divisor in <m>R</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    Although you might guess that this same argument could be employed to prove the reverse implication, we are foiled by the fact that <m>A^\dagger</m> can be the zero matrix even when <m>\det A</m> is nonzero! (This is true even in the familiar setting <m>R=\R</m>.) The reader is invited to check out this <url href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/71740/necessary-and-sufficient-condition-for-trivial-kernel-of-a-matrix-over-a-commutat/71741">StackExchange</url> post, which provides an answer as well as some useful references. 
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<proposition xml:id="prop_zero_divisors_cancellation">
    <title>Cancellation of non-zero divisors</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Assume <m>a</m> is a nonzero element of the ring <m>R</m> and is not a zero divisor. For all <m>b,c\in R</m> if <m>ab=ac</m> or <m>ba=ca</m>, then <m>b=c</m>. Using logical shorthand: 
            <md>
                <mrow> ab=ac \text{ or } ba=ca \implies b=c </mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</proposition>
<theorem xml:id="th_finite_rings_fields">
<title>Finite integral domains</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a finite commutative ring. The following statements are equivalent. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>R</m> is an integral domain.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>R</m> is a field. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<definition xml:id="d_nilpotents_idempotents">
<title>Nilpotents and idempotents</title>
<statement>
<p>
An element <m>a</m> of the ring <m>R</m> is <term>nilpotent</term> if <m>a^n=0</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>; it is <term>idempotent</term> if <m>a^2=a</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>



